11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#$\"+L06/O!\")" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
229 "2.  Polynomials:  Intercepts and Sign.  There are several feature
s about the graphs of polynomials which are important to track.  These
 features inform us about the behavior of the function.  Those feature
s include the following:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 57 "    a.    x-intercepts of the function            \+
       " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 129 "                       Those \+
values where the graph crosses the x-axis.  Those points are solutions
 of the equation y = f(x) = 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    b.
    regions (intervals) in the domain of the function where the values
 of the function are positive" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "       \+
                Those regions where the graph lies above the x-axis.  \+
For a continuous function, and in particular for polynomials, these re
gions are bounded by the intercepts and may stretch to +/- infinity." 
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    c.    regions (intervals) in the d
omain of the function where the values of the function are negative" }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "                       Those regions wh
ere the graph lies below the x-axis.  For a continuous function, and i
n particular for polynomials, these regions are bounded by the interce
pts and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 36 " \+
   d.   y-intercept of the function" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 107 " \+
                      The value where the graph crosses the y-axis.  T
he value of the function when x = 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 19 " \+
   e.   end limits" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 384 "                  \+
     For a polynomial, its values will become either arbitrarily large
 in a positive sense or arbitrarily large in a negative sense as the d
omain values tend to infinity.  Graphically, the values on the graph w
ill growth arbitrarily large positively (go up off the graph) or arbit
rarily large negative (go down off the graph) as the domain values ten
d to infinity.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 87 "                     \+
  Similar behavior holds true for approaches to negative infinity." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 150 "For each
 of the following polynomials,  provide a graph of the polynomial.  Ch
oose a range that will optimally represent the features of the graph. \+
  " }{TEXT 268 4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 90 ", for each polynomial find each \+
of the above five graphcial characteristics (a.  thru e.):" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "a.   " }{XPPEDIT 
18 0 "y = 6*x^2+24*x-8" "6#/%\"yG,(*&\"\"'\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"\"#F(F(*&\"#C
